rs and sinoatrial node"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft heart chambers and anterior septum\u003C/strong\u003E receive blood from the left coronary artery via its two main branches:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELeft anterior descending artery - supplies the anterior interventricular septum and anterior wall of left ventricle\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECircumflex artery - supplies the lateral wall of left ventricle and left atrium\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight ventricle and posterior septum\u003C/strong\u003E are supplied by the right coronary artery\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth ventricles and entire septum\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the right ventricle receives blood from the right coronary artery\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight heart chambers and sinoatrial node\u003C/strong\u003E are supplied by branches of the right coronary artery\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac conduction system only\u003C/strong\u003E receives blood supply primarily from the right coronary artery\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this vascular distribution is clinically important as it determines which areas of heart muscle are affected by coronary artery occlusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The left coronary artery divides into the left anterior descending and circumflex arteries to supply the left ventricle and anterior septum.","The left anterior descending artery supplies the anterior wall and anterior interventricular septum.","The circumflex artery supplies the lateral wall of the left ventricle and left atrium."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John 